x4freetext: Experiment performed at the white
source neutron beam at the LANSCE/WNR facility using
gamma-ray spectrometer GEANIE
The target cell containing the 86Kr isotopically
enriched gas consisted of one cylinder, 6.261 cm long
and with a radius of 1.7975 cm. The cylindrical
horizontal walls were 0.525-mm thick and made of
aluminum. The planar walls, orthogonal to the neutron
beam, were very thin mylar foils. The pressure of the
86Kr gas inside the cell was approx. 450 kPa. During
two days of the experiment two natural Fe 5-cm
circular foils, 0.05 mm thick, were placed in the
front and back of the 86Kr gas cell for monitor
purposes
GEANIE was comprised of 10 Compton-suppressed
planar Ge detectors (Low Energy Photon Spectrometers -
LEPS) and 10 Compton-suppressed coaxial Ge
detectors. During experiment only coaxial detectors
were used. GEANIE was located 20.34 m from the WNR
spallation neutron source on the 60R (60deg-Right)
flight path.
neutron energy determined by time of flight
method. Detection time of the "flash" of gamma rays
caused by the spallation reaction was used as a
reference marker. The detection time of the gamma
rays produced by neutrons interacting with the sample
was used to calculate the time of flight.
For normalization
purpose the natural Fe 5 cm diameter foil, 0.05 mm
thick, was placed in front and back of gas cell.
The 846.8 keV, 2+ -> 0+ transition of 56Fe was used to
normalize the cross sections.

x4freetext: Pulsed neutron beam was produced via
spallation on a natural W target by an 800-MeV proton
linear accelerator beam. The average proton beam
current at the spallation target was about 1 - 2
mu-A. The neutron beam structure contained 625 mu-s
long `macropulses` driven by two of every three such
macropulses from the accelerator for an average rate
of 40/s. Each macropulse consisted of `micropulses`
spaced every 1.8 mu-s, each <1 ns long. The pulsed
beam allowed incident neutron energies to be
determined using the time-of-flight technique.
Corrections for the finite beam spot size, gamma ray
attenuation in the target (both Kr and Fe), and the
contribution from neutrons produced by scattering and
reactions in the targets (secondary effects) were
modeled using the MCNPX Monte Carlo radiation
transport code.
Matrix of gamma-ray energy versus TOF was built for
the coaxial detectors. By gating on the TOF axis,
gamma ray spectra corresponding to selected neutron
energy bins were obtained.
